3.2 PURPOSE AND OBJECTIVE OF THE PROCUREMENT

The Chief Technology Officer is seeking the development of a new
website on a WordPress platform that will provide a user driven experience that will act as a
platform for engagement and education of the HHS innovation initiatives. The new website will
provide a more information centric approach that will also provide a more user centric
experience for people visiting the new **<AGENCY NAME>** web site.

3.3 REPORTING REQUIREMENTS AND TASKS
The Contractor will work with senior staff at the PSC Office of the Director (PSC OD) regarding
specific guidance and comments for reporting. At a minimum, the Contractor’s recruitment
activities will include the following specific tasks:
3.3.1 Post Award Meeting
After the initial award, the selected contractor will meet with the Contracting
Officer(CO) and Contracting Officer’s Representative (COR) no later than 7 days after
the contract award date to discuss the vision and timelines for the project.
3.3.2 Weekly Project Meeting
Once a week for one hour the web designer will meet with the COR to provide a status
report of the project. Time will also be used to resolve any outstanding issues or
questions from the previous week.
3.3.3 Existing Audience Analysis
A report detailing the analysis of www.hhs.gov/open's audiences clearly presenting in its
text user personas to provide better understanding of the Department of Health and
Human Services stakeholders and interest groups. This report will guide the strategic
content creation, user interface design and overall themes of the other Deliverable
Products outlined below.

3.3.4 Information Architecture
Information architecture (IA) and initial site map for the new HHS Innovations site. This IA and site map will be used so copy can be revised and/or developed in-house while the
contractor is in the process of executing other deliverable products. IA and site map will
include content currently in the www.hhs.gov/open website and new content currently
not on the www.hhs.gov/open website.
3.3.5 Design Elements and Mood/Storyboarding
Initial design elements to be incorporated into the current infrastructure. In order to
generate internal stakeholder interest in, and adoption of, the process, small changes to
the organization and design of the current site will be developed and implemented as
recommended based on the findings in Deliverable Product #1.
3.3.6 Page Templating
Complete development page templates for outreach materials on a WordPress platform.
This includes the complete website, features, applications, blog, mobile, and any items
deemed best to connect with the audiences identified in Deliverable Product #1.
Note that this deliverable may be subject to multiple rounds of revisions and requires a
unique look and feel and creative materials submitted that clearly resemble other
government or mission-related sites will not be accepted. Further, all materials are
required to be ready for technical implementation upon delivery and will not approve hours billed to make corrections to templated work or incorrectly formatted items.
3.3.7 Usability and Compliance Testing
A usability report detailing initial audience response and metrics pertaining to the
development of the HHS innovations website and any strategic recommendations and/or
modifications to address issues as necessary.
3.3.8 Style and Brand Guidelines
Brand guidelines; a comprehensive manual for staff outlining the specifications and
recommended use of all creative to develop and maintain the new corporate identity.
3.3.9 Final Summary Report
The contractor shall submit a draft of the final project report to the CO and COR later
than 20 days prior to the end of the contract period. The contractor shall submit a final
report no later than 5 days prior to the end of the contract period. The final report shall
include the existing audience analysis, a description of the work done, recommendations
for future enhance to the HHS innovations website.

